networkx Library¶

  1. Study of the structure networks
  2. Can work as a back-end/front-end visualization design
  3. The outputs can are standard input for graphi visualization softwares
  4. The output can be used for visualization using D3js
  5. It is open source!

In [14]:
# nodes can be added from a list, which is very helpful in case of adding thousands of nodes
f,ax = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(10,10))
nx.draw(G,pos=nx.spring_layout(G),with_labels=True,node_size=200,alpha=.5,ax=ax[0][0])
ax[0][0].set_title('Spring layout')
nx.draw(G,pos=nx.random_layout(G),node_size=30,alpha=.5,ax=ax[0][1])
ax[0][1].set_title('Random layout')
nx.draw(G,pos=nx.shell_layout(G),node_size=30,alpha=.5,ax=ax[1][0])
ax[1][0].set_title('Shell layout')
nx.draw(G,pos=nx.fruchterman_reingold_layout(G),node_size=30,alpha=.5,ax=ax[1][1])
ax[1][1].set_title('Fruchterman Reingold layout');

In [50]:
G = nx.random_geometric_graph(200, 0.125)
f,ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,5))
pos = nx.spring_layout(G) ## layout position
# nodes
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos,
                       nodelist=range(1,100), ## plot range of 1-100 of the nodes
                       node_color='r', ## set color to red
                       node_size=80,
                       alpha=0.3,
                      ax=ax)

nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos,
                       nodelist=range(100,200),## plot range of 100-200 of the nodes
                       node_color='b', ## set color to blue
                       node_size=80,
                       alpha=0.5,
                      ax=ax);

In [59]:
# Author: Aric Hagberg (hagberg@lanl.gov)
G = nx.cubical_graph()
pos = nx.spring_layout(G)  # positions for all nodes
# nodes
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos,nodelist=[0, 1, 2, 3],node_color='r',
                       node_size=500,alpha=0.6)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos,nodelist=[4, 5, 6, 7],node_color='b',
                       node_size=500,alpha=0.6)
# edges
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, width=1.0, alpha=0.5)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos,edgelist=[(0, 1), (1, 2), (2, 3), (3, 0)],
                       width=8, alpha=0.3, edge_color='r')
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos,edgelist=[(4, 5), (5, 6), (6, 7), (7, 4)],
                       width=8, alpha=0.3, edge_color='b')
# some math labels
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, labels, font_size=16)
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

{"id": "Dave", "gender": "M", "age":24}
]
Links = [
{"Src": "Bob", "Dest": "Alice", "Mutual_Friends": 5},
{"Src": "Eve", "Dest": "Bob", "Mutual_Friends": 2},
{"Src": "Eve", "Dest": "Alice", "Mutual_Friends": 2},
{"Src": "Dave", "Dest": "Bob", "Mutual_Friends": 4}]
In [97]:
col_dict = {'M':'steelblue','F':'pink'}
## adding options to nodes and edges
for row in Nodes:
    G.add_node(row['id'], size = row['age'], 
               gender = col_dict[row['gender']])
for row in Links:
    G.add_edge(row['Src'],row['Dest'],
               weight = row['Mutual_Friends'])
print(nx.info(G))
